column1: Fulani are a nomadic ethnic group found mainly in West Africa, Central Africa, and North Africa. They have traditionally been herders of livestock such as cattle, goats, sheep, and camels. The term "Fulani" is derived from the Arabic word "fulan," which means "cowherd." Fulani people have historically faced discrimination and marginalization in many parts of their traditional range due to their cultural practices and economic activities. In recent years, there has been an increase in attacks on Fulani communities by farmers and herdsmen in several countries including Nigeria, Mali, Burkina Faso, and Cameroon. This has led to displacement and loss of life for many Fulani people.
